Youth Report: Coding & Visualizations Guidelines

This document contains all coding & visualization guidelines. There are implementation example at every step.

1. Folder Structure

There are 3 data sets we are using: data_general.csv, data_identity.csv, data_marriage.csv. All of these should be stored with the exact name inside a folder names data in your working directory. Each findings group should have all their code in single R file.

2. Data Import

If you have followed the previous rule, below is how you will be importing the data. Use the same variable names to store the data as shown below, so that there is some basic similarity in our scripts.

data_general <- read_csv("data/data_general.csv")
data_identity <- read_csv("data/data_identity.csv")
data_marriage <- read_csv("data/data_marriage.csv")

3. Comments

Please make sure your code is commented in detail. This will make it easy for someone else who will look at your code and also if you look at your own code after a long time

4. Code Sections

Since there is a lot of code, adding sections in your R Script spares a lot of headache to find code for each plot. This is easy to implement in RStudio: press Ctrl + Shift + R on Windows or Cmd + Shift + R on Mac. A dialogue box will appear, in which you will add the section title and press OK. The section title will appear in a line.

You can add extra # in that line to convert into sub headings

You can navigate through your document with these headings using this button on the bottom left of your code pane:

5. Select Top ~5 Categories

Too many categories in graph cause too much clutter. Select few of them. 5 is generally a good number, but you can have a little more if you feel necessary.

If you are selecting top few categories, you can do that using slice_max(<column-with-values>, n = <how-many-values>)

Example

I am creating a graph showing the percentage of people interested to learn specific vocational skills. In last line, I select 5 skills with highest percentage of people interested:

num_interested <- # Number of people interested in skill development programs
  data_general |>
  filter(interest_skill_program == "yes") |>
  nrow()
  
data_general |> 
  filter(interest_skill_program == "yes") |> # take only interested people
  select(choice_skill_program) |>  # select relevant row
  separate_rows(choice_skill_program, sep = " ") |> # separate rows as 1 person could have multiple interests
  
  count(choice_skill_program) |> # count number of those interested in each program
  mutate(percentage = (n / num_interested) * 100) |>  # find percentage out of those interestes
  filter(!is.na(choice_skill_program)) |>  # remove NA values
  slice_max(percentage, n = 5)  # slice top 5 skills with highest interest
# A tibble: 5 Ã 3
  choice_skill_program     n percentage
  <chr>                <int>      <dbl>
1 computer_skill         239       48.0
2 beautician             146       29.3
3 sports                 140       28.1
4 english                135       27.1
5 tailoring              129       25.9
Note

This pipe can be continued into a ggplot() function to create a graph. I will show how to do that later.

6. Format Category Names

All variables in the data set are stored in snake case, which_looks_like_this. This is because it is easy to code when things are in this format. However, it is also not pleasant to look at.

So we have to manually change each of the category we are showing in our graph. This shouldnât be hard if you followed the previous rule and selected top 5 things. You can rename the categories using a case_when() inside the mutate() function (see example)

Note

case_when() is very similar to ifelse(). Just that it makes the job much easier when we have multiple cases.

Example

Using the previous example, I got to know what the top 5 interests are. Repeating that here.

Click to see code 
num_interested <- # Number of people interested in skill development programs
  data_general |>
  filter(interest_skill_program == "yes") |>
  nrow()
  
data_general |> 
  filter(interest_skill_program == "yes") |> # take only interested people
  select(choice_skill_program) |>  # select relevant row
  separate_rows(choice_skill_program, sep = " ") |> # separate rows as 1 person could have multiple interests
  
  count(choice_skill_program) |> # count number of those interested in each program
  mutate(percentage = (n / num_interested) * 100) |>  # find percentage out of those interestes
  filter(!is.na(choice_skill_program)) |>  # remove NA values
  slice_max(percentage, n = 5)  # slice top 5 skills with highest interest
# A tibble: 5 Ã 3
  choice_skill_program     n percentage
  <chr>                <int>      <dbl>
1 computer_skill         239       48.0
2 beautician             146       29.3
3 sports                 140       28.1
4 english                135       27.1
5 tailoring              129       25.9

Now we will change each of these manually using case_when() inside a mutate(). It is implemented between lines 11 & 19. Then we will plot the graph.

data_general |> 
  filter(interest_skill_program == "yes") |> # take only interested people
  select(choice_skill_program) |>  # select relevant row
  separate_rows(choice_skill_program, sep = " ") |> # separate rows as 1 person could have multiple interests
  
  count(choice_skill_program) |> # count number of those interested in each program
  mutate(percentage = (n / num_interested) * 100) |>  # find percentage out of those interestes
  filter(!is.na(choice_skill_program)) |>  # remove NA values
  slice_max(percentage, n = 5) |> # slice top 5 skills with highest interest
  
  mutate(choice_skill_program = case_when( # Capitalize and space top 5 skills
    choice_skill_program == "computer_skill" ~ "Computer Skills",
    choice_skill_program == "beautician" ~ "Beautician",
    choice_skill_program == "sports" ~ "Sports",
    choice_skill_program == "english" ~ "English",
    choice_skill_program == "tailoring" ~ "Tailoring",
    .default = choice_skill_program # if none of the above match, keep as it is
    )
  ) |> 
  
  ggplot(
    aes(
      x = choice_skill_program, 
      y = percentage
      )) +
  geom_col()

Here you can also see how we continue the pipe into the ggplot() function to plot our modified data.

7. Order Categories

It is usually a good idea to order the categories as per their values. This can be done using fct_reorder() when setting the aes() of your ggplot() function

Note

Sometimes ordering according to numbers/percentages is not the best way to do things. Say, you are plotting the education level of our demographics. In this case, ordering the categories from lowest to highest education level is a better way to do it rather than ordering them according to which level has the highest number of people

Example

Reordering the categories in the previous example based on percentage of people interested. This is implemented in line 23 below.

data_general |> 
  filter(interest_skill_program == "yes") |> # take only interested people
  select(choice_skill_program) |>  # select relevant row
  separate_rows(choice_skill_program, sep = " ") |> # separate rows as 1 person could have multiple interests
  
  count(choice_skill_program) |> # count number of those interested in each program
  mutate(percentage = (n / num_interested) * 100) |>  # find percentage out of those interestes
  filter(!is.na(choice_skill_program)) |>  # remove NA values
  slice_max(percentage, n = 5) |> # slice top 5 skills with highest interest
  
  mutate(choice_skill_program = case_when( # Capitalize and space top 5 skills
    choice_skill_program == "computer_skill" ~ "Computer Skills",
    choice_skill_program == "beautician" ~ "Beautician",
    choice_skill_program == "sports" ~ "Sports",
    choice_skill_program == "english" ~ "English",
    choice_skill_program == "tailoring" ~ "Tailoring",
    .default = choice_skill_program # if none of the above match, keep as it is
    )
  ) |> 
  
  ggplot(
    aes(
      x = fct_reorder(choice_skill_program, percentage), # order skills as per percentage of interest
      y = percentage
      )) +
  geom_col()

8. Format X & Y Labels

The labels in the X & Y axis also need to be formatted with proper case and spacing. This can be done by adding xlab() and ylab() to the plot

Example

Setting X & Y axis labels in the previous example in line 27 & 28 below.

data_general |> 
  filter(interest_skill_program == "yes") |> # take only interested people
  select(choice_skill_program) |>  # select relevant row
  separate_rows(choice_skill_program, sep = " ") |> # separate rows as 1 person could have multiple interests
  
  count(choice_skill_program) |> # count number of those interested in each program
  mutate(percentage = (n / num_interested) * 100) |>  # find percentage out of those interestes
  filter(!is.na(choice_skill_program)) |>  # remove NA values
  slice_max(percentage, n = 5) |> # slice top 5 skills with highest interest
  
  mutate(choice_skill_program = case_when( # Capitalize and space top 5 skills
    choice_skill_program == "computer_skill" ~ "Computer Skills",
    choice_skill_program == "beautician" ~ "Beautician",
    choice_skill_program == "sports" ~ "Sports",
    choice_skill_program == "english" ~ "English",
    choice_skill_program == "tailoring" ~ "Tailoring",
    .default = choice_skill_program # if none of the above match, keep as it is
    )
  ) |> 
  
  ggplot(
    aes(
      x = fct_reorder(choice_skill_program, percentage), # order skills as per percentage of interest
      y = percentage
      )) +
  geom_col() +
  xlab("Skills") + 
  ylab("Percentage of Interested Respondents")

9. Flip Coordinates

Bar/Column charts should be flipped in general. This especially helps if the category name is long, it sits better in the y-axis. This can be achieved by adding coord_flip() to the plot.

Example

Flipping the previous graph in line 29 below.

data_general |> 
  filter(interest_skill_program == "yes") |> # take only interested people
  select(choice_skill_program) |>  # select relevant row
  separate_rows(choice_skill_program, sep = " ") |> # separate rows as 1 person could have multiple interests
  
  count(choice_skill_program) |> # count number of those interested in each program
  mutate(percentage = (n / num_interested) * 100) |>  # find percentage out of those interestes
  filter(!is.na(choice_skill_program)) |>  # remove NA values
  slice_max(percentage, n = 5) |> # slice top 5 skills with highest interest
  
  mutate(choice_skill_program = case_when( # Capitalize and space top 5 skills
    choice_skill_program == "computer_skill" ~ "Computer Skills",
    choice_skill_program == "beautician" ~ "Beautician",
    choice_skill_program == "sports" ~ "Sports",
    choice_skill_program == "english" ~ "English",
    choice_skill_program == "tailoring" ~ "Tailoring",
    .default = choice_skill_program # if none of the above match, keep as it is
    )
  ) |> 
  
  ggplot(
    aes(
      x = fct_reorder(choice_skill_program, percentage), # order skills as per percentage of interest
      y = percentage
      )) +
  geom_col() +
  xlab("Skills") + 
  ylab("Percentage of Interested Respondents") +
  coord_flip()

10. Color Scheme (Most Important!!)

Below you will find the hex-values of colors to be used. It depends on how many colors your graph needs (which depends on the number of stacks your graph will have)

Only 1 stack: "#7e3717" OR "#5d6736"

2 stacks: "#7e3717", "#3f1816" OR "#ebdcc5", "#5d6736"

3 stacks: "#e5aa7b", "#7e3717", "#3f1816"

4 stacks: "#e5aa7b", "#7e3717", "#3f1816", "#5d6736"

5 stacks: "#ebdcc5", "#e5aa7b", "#7e3717", "#3f1816", "#5d6736"

Graphs with 1 or 2 colors would be the most common. So we have provided two choices for each of these. You can alternate between them so that the report doesnât look monotonic.

If your graph has only 1 color, you cans set it using the fill parameter. If your graph has multiple colors, you have to add scale_fill_manual(values = <color_vector>) with all the colors to the plot.

Example

Single Stack Graph

Using the previous example with both the colors separately. The fill parameter has been implemented on line 26 with "#7e3717" color.

data_general |>

  mutate(percentage = (n / num_interested) * 100) |>  # find percentage out of those interestes
  filter(!is.na(choice_skill_program)) |>  # remove NA values

    choice_skill_program == "computer_skill" ~ "Computer Skills",
    choice_skill_program == "beautician" ~ "Beautician",
    choice_skill_program == "sports" ~ "Sports",
    choice_skill_program == "english" ~ "English",
    choice_skill_program == "tailoring" ~ "Tailoring",
    .default = choice_skill_program # if none of the above match, keep as it is

    aes(
      x = fct_reorder(choice_skill_program, percentage), # order skills as per percentage of interest

11. Add & Format Data Labels

You need to add data labels to the graph so that exact values can be shown. Moreover, the values have to be rounded to the nearest whole number.

This section has a mouthful of code, so do see the examples.

If you are using geom_col(), this can be done by adding geom_text(aes(label = round(<y-axis-column>)), hjust = <some-negative-value>) to the plot.

If you are using geom_bar() without a specific y column , you have to add use geom_text(stat = "count", aes(label = after_stat(count)), hjust = <some-negative-value>) instead.

Difference between geom_col() and geom_bar()

In geom_col() you need to mention both the x & y axis columns in the aes(). But in geom_bar(), you usually mention only the x axis column in the aes(). The y axis in geom_bar()by default is the count of the categories mentioned in the x axis. (In other words, geom_bar() creates a frequency plot by default.)

You can add certain arguments to geom_bar() to make it behave like geom_col(), but I will not cover that here. In general: Use geom_col() if you have columns for both x & y values and use geom_bar() if you want the y axis to have a count of x axis values.

In our examples, I have used geom_col() for the Vocational Skills, and geom_bar() for mock_data.

If your graph doesnât have flipped coordinates, use vjust instead of hjust. They should have a negative value because we need the labels above the bars.

If your graph has multiple stacks side by side, you have to add a position = position_dodge(width = <some-value>) argument to geom_text() so that the labels donât overlap.

Again, this is a little tricky to understand, so donât worry if you didnât understand and see the examples.

Examples

geom_col(), Single Stack

Using the vocational skills example which uses geom_col() with only single stack. Labels have been implemented between lines 29 & 32.

data_general |> 
  filter(interest_skill_program == "yes") |> # take only interested people
  select(choice_skill_program) |>  # select relevant row
  separate_rows(choice_skill_program, sep = " ") |> # separate rows as 1 person could have multiple interests
  
  count(choice_skill_program) |> # count number of those interested in each program
  mutate(percentage = (n / num_interested) * 100) |>  # find percentage out of those interestes
  filter(!is.na(choice_skill_program)) |>  # remove NA values
  slice_max(percentage, n = 5) |> # slice top 5 skills with highest interest
  
  mutate(choice_skill_program = case_when( # Capitalize and space top 5 skills
    choice_skill_program == "computer_skill" ~ "Computer Skills",
    choice_skill_program == "beautician" ~ "Beautician",
    choice_skill_program == "sports" ~ "Sports",
    choice_skill_program == "english" ~ "English",
    choice_skill_program == "tailoring" ~ "Tailoring",
    .default = choice_skill_program # if none of the above match, keep as it is
    )
  ) |> 
  
  ggplot(
    aes(
      x = fct_reorder(choice_skill_program, percentage), # order skills as per percentage of interest
      y = percentage
      )) +
  geom_col(fill = "#7e3717") +
  xlab("Skills") + 
  ylab("Percentage") + 
  geom_text(
    aes(label = round(percentage)), #use percentage as labels
    hjust = -0.3 # adjust horizontal position of labels
    ) +
  coord_flip()

geom_bar(), Single Stack

Using the mock_data example with a single stack. Labels have been implemented between lines 5 & 9.

ggplot(mock_data, aes(x = x_val)) +
  geom_bar(fill = "#5d6736") +
  xlab("Values") + ylab("Count") +
  ylim(0, 150) +
  geom_text(
    stat = "count",
    aes(label = after_stat(count)),
    hjust = -0.3) +
  coord_flip()

geom_bar(), Multiple Stack

Using the mock_data example with a single stack. Labels have been implemented between lines 5 & 9.

ggplot(mock_data, aes(x = x_val, fill = five_types)) +
  geom_bar(position = "dodge") +
  xlab("Values") + ylab("Count") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("#ebdcc5", "#e5aa7b", "#7e3717", "#3f1816", "#5d6736")) +
  geom_text(
    stat = "count",
    aes(label = after_stat(count)),
    position = position_dodge(width = 0.9), 
    hjust = -0.3) +
  coord_flip()
Note

I have not implemented labels in geom_col() with multiple stacks. It is very similar to the first example here, except that you have to also add position = position_dodge(width = <some-value>) inside the geom_text()

12. Visibility of Labels (Required sometimes)

Sometimes the label are not visible because they get outside the bounds of the plot. In this case, it can be fixed by adding ylim(<min-y>, <max-y>) to the plot

Example

Notice this graph:

Click to see code 
ggplot(mock_data, aes(x = x_val)) +
  geom_bar(fill = "#5d6736") +
  xlab("Values") + ylab("Count") +
  geom_text(
    stat = "count",
    aes(label = after_stat(count)),
    hjust = -0.3) +
  coord_flip()

See how the labels for x3 & x4 are hidden. To fix that, we will add ylim() to the plot, as in line 4below.

ggplot(mock_data, aes(x = x_val)) +
  geom_bar(fill = "#5d6736") +
  xlab("Values") + ylab("Count") +
  ylim(0, 150) +
  geom_text(
    stat = "count",
    aes(label = after_stat(count)),
    hjust = -0.3) +
  coord_flip()

13. Format Legend

Proper casing and spacing also has to be implemented in the legend if you have a multi-stacked graph. The title can be changed using guides(fill = guide_legend(title = "<legend-tile>")).

Each key in the legend can be changed by modifying the relevant column with case_when(), similar to how we previously did in 5. Format Category Names

Example

Changing the legend title in line 10 below:

ggplot(mock_data, aes(x = x_val, fill = five_types)) +
  geom_bar(position = "dodge") +
  xlab("Values") + ylab("Count") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("#ebdcc5", "#e5aa7b", "#7e3717", "#3f1816", "#5d6736")) +
  geom_text(
    stat = "count",
    aes(label = after_stat(count)),
    position = position_dodge(width = 0.9), 
    hjust = -0.3) +
  guides(fill = guide_legend(title = "Type")) +
  coord_flip()
Note

In this case the key of the legend is need not be modified because the data in the tibble column is in proper format already. But in most cases, you have to modify it with a pipe before implementing the ggplot() function; similar to 5. Format Category Names

14. Theme Settings

The following theme features have to be added: Times New Roman font with size 13, no grid lines, transparent background & box for legend. This can be implemented by adding theme_classic() + theme(text = element_text(family = "serif", size = 13), panel.background = element_rect(fill = "transparent"), plot.background = element_rect(fill = "transparent", color = NA), legend.background = element_rect(fill = "transparent", color = NA), legend.box.background = element_rect(fill = "transparent", color = "black")) to the plot.

Example

See lines 11 to 16 below:

ggplot(mock_data, aes(x = x_val, fill = five_types)) +
  geom_bar(position = "dodge") +
  xlab("Values") + ylab("Count") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("#ebdcc5", "#e5aa7b", "#7e3717", "#3f1816", "#5d6736")) +
  geom_text(
    stat = "count",
    aes(label = after_stat(count)),
    position = position_dodge(width = 0.9), 
    hjust = -0.3) +
  guides(fill = guide_legend(title = "Category")) +
  theme_classic() +
  theme(text = element_text(family = "serif", size = 13),
        panel.background = element_rect(fill = "transparent"),
        plot.background = element_rect(fill = "transparent", color = NA),
        legend.background = element_rect(fill = "transparent", color = NA),
        legend.box.background = element_rect(fill = "transparent", color = "black")) +
  coord_flip()

Bonus: Graphs with all features

In all the above examples, I have added the features one by one so that you can see what changes are happening at every step. However, if you want all the the features in one place as a template, see below.

Vocational Skills

The vocational skills example:

num_interested <- # Number of people interested in skill development programs
  data_general |>
  filter(interest_skill_program == "yes") |>
  nrow()
  

data_general |> 
  filter(interest_skill_program == "yes") |> # take only interested people
  select(choice_skill_program) |>  # select relevant row
  separate_rows(choice_skill_program, sep = " ") |> # separate rows as 1 person could have multiple interests
  
  count(choice_skill_program) |> # count number of those interested in each program
  mutate(percentage = (n / num_interested) * 100) |>  # find percentage out of those interested
  filter(!is.na(choice_skill_program)) |>  # remove NA values
  slice_max(percentage, n = 5) |> # slice top 5 skills with highest interest
  
  mutate(choice_skill_program = case_when( # Capitalize and space top 5 skills
    choice_skill_program == "computer_skill" ~ "Computer Skills",
    choice_skill_program == "beautician" ~ "Beautician",
    choice_skill_program == "sports" ~ "Sports",
    choice_skill_program == "english" ~ "English",
    choice_skill_program == "tailoring" ~ "Tailoring",
    .default = choice_skill_program # if none of the above match, keep as it is
    )
  ) |> 
  
  ggplot(
    aes(
      x = fct_reorder(choice_skill_program, percentage), # order skills as per percentage of interest
      y = percentage
      )) +
  geom_col(fill = "#7e3717") +
  xlab("Skills") + 
  ylab("Percentage of Interested Respondents") + 
  geom_text(
    aes(label = round(percentage)), #use percentage as labels
    hjust = -0.5 # adjust horizontal position of labels
    ) +
  guides(fill = guide_legend(title = "Types")) +
  theme_classic() +
  theme(text = element_text(family = "serif", size = 13),
        panel.background = element_rect(fill = "transparent"),
        plot.background = element_rect(fill = "transparent", color = NA),
        legend.background = element_rect(fill = "transparent", color = NA),
        legend.box.background = element_rect(fill = "transparent", color = "black")) +
  coord_flip()

15. Save Transparent Image

The images have to be downloaded preserving the transparency. To do this, you have to assign a name to the plot. Then run ggsave("<filename>.png", plot = <assigned-name> , bg = "transparent")

Label Visibility in Saved Plots

Sometimes, the labels appear properly in RStudio but get hidden when downloaded as image. In this case, add ylim() as instructed in 12. Visibility of Labels

16. Consider Proper Relevance

It is a very common pitfall to only consider the variables we are plotting and forget about the previous relevance that were used in creating the form. Avoid this, and apply filter() with appropriate relevance when required.

Example

In the vocational skills examples I used above, I have always considered only the set of respondents who showed interest in learning vocational skills as the denominator. See lines 3 and 8.

num_interested <- # Number of people interested in skill development programs
  data_general |>
  filter(interest_skill_program == "yes") |>
  nrow()
  

data_general |> 
  filter(interest_skill_program == "yes") |> # take only interested people
  select(choice_skill_program) |>  # select relevant row
  separate_rows(choice_skill_program, sep = " ") |> # separate rows as 1 person could have multiple interests
  
  count(choice_skill_program) |> # count number of those interested in each program
  mutate(percentage = (n / num_interested) * 100) |>  # find percentage out of those interested
  filter(!is.na(choice_skill_program)) |>  # remove NA values
  slice_max(percentage, n = 5) |> # slice top 5 skills with highest interest
  
  mutate(choice_skill_program = case_when( # Capitalize and space top 5 skills
    choice_skill_program == "computer_skill" ~ "Computer Skills",
    choice_skill_program == "beautician" ~ "Beautician",
    choice_skill_program == "sports" ~ "Sports",
    choice_skill_program == "english" ~ "English",
    choice_skill_program == "tailoring" ~ "Tailoring",
    .default = choice_skill_program # if none of the above match, keep as it is
    )
  ) |> 
  
  ggplot(
    aes(
      x = fct_reorder(choice_skill_program, percentage), # order skills as per percentage of interest
      y = percentage
      )) +

  xlab("Skills") + 
  ylab("Percentage") + 
  geom_text(
    aes(label = round(percentage)), #use percentage as labels
    hjust = -0.5 # adjust horizontal position of labels
    ) +
  guides(fill = guide_legend(title = "Types")) +
  theme_classic() +
  theme(text = element_text(family = "serif", size = 13),
        panel.background = element_rect(fill = "transparent"),
        plot.background = element_rect(fill = "transparent", color = NA),
        legend.background = element_rect(fill = "transparent", color = NA),
        legend.box.background = element_rect(fill = "transparent", color = "black")) +
  coord_flip()

17. Figure Numbering & Title

Your figures need to numbered and have a one line title, along with the sample size. This should be written below the image in the google doc (and NOT coded in R). It needs to be in the format Figure <topic-number>.<figure-number>: <figure-title> (n = <sample-size>).

Donât code titles

The titling should NOT be coded using labs() into your R script. Write it below the graph on goole docs instead. This will make it easy because to modify things like figure numbering later.

Example

The vocational skill plot we have been using is, say, the second graph under the âSkill & Vocational Trainingâ topic. This is the fourth topic in the âFindingsâ Section of our outline. Hence, I will title it as Figure 4.2: Top 5 Vocational Skills with Highest Interest (n = 498).

18. Note Explaining the Figure (Rarely Required)

If you have a very complicated visualization, you can provide a short paragraph explaining it. This is usually not required. Avoid it as much as possible by creating visualizations that are easy to understand.

Example

19. Non Visualization Code

A lot of information in the report need not be presented through graphs & visualizations as they can be written in one line. However, your R script should contain sections with the code you used extract this info.

Example

In the report, say I mention 74% of our respondents were interested to learn a vocational skill.

# Percentage of Interest in Vocational Skills -----------------------------

num_total <- data_general |> nrow() # Sample size

num_interested <- # No. of respondents interested in vocational skills
  data_general |> 
  filter(interest_skill_program == "yes") |> 
  nrow()

(num_interested/num_total) * 100 # Calculating percentage
